V{{Infobox philosopher\u000a|region           = \u000a|era              = \u000a|image       =\u000a|image_size       = \u000a|caption     = \u000a|name             = Jonathan Wolff\u000a|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1959|6|25|df=y}}\u000a|birth_place      = \u000a|death_date       = \u000a|death_place      =\u000a|nationality      = British\u000a|institution      = [[University College London]]\u000a|alma_mater       = [[University College London]]\u000a|school_tradition = \u000a|main_interests   = [[Political philosophy]]\u000a|notable_ideas    = \u000a|influences       = \u000a|influenced       = \u000a|signature        = \u000a}}\u000a\u000a'''Jonathan Wolff''' (born 25 June 1959) is a British philosopher and academic. He is Professor of Philosophy and [[Dean (education)|Dean]] of the Faculty of Arts and Humanities at [[University College London]].\u000a\u000a==Life and Career==\u000aWolff was born on 25 June 1959 to Herbert Wolff and Doris Wolff (née Polakoff).<ref name="Who's Who 2014">{{cite web|title=WOLFF, Prof. Jonathan|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U4000304|website=Who's Who 2014|publisher=A & C Black|accessdate=25 June 2014|date=December 2013}}</ref> He earned his [[MPhil]] from [[University College London|UCL]]<ref name="UCL homepage">{{cite web | first=Jonathan | last=Wolff | title=Personal Homepage | url = http://www.homepages.ucl.ac.uk/~uctyjow/ | publisher= University College London | accessdate=2007-12-11}}</ref> under the direction of [[G.A. Cohen]] in 1985.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Grady|first1=Jane|title=GA Cohen|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/aug/10/ga-cohen-obituary|accessdate=25 June 2014|work=The Guardian|date=10 August 2009}}</ref>  Apart from one year as a Harkness Fellow at Harvard University, he has taught at UCL ever since.  As of September 1, 2016, he will take up the Blavatnik Chair in Public Policy in the [[Blavatnik School of Government]] at [[Oxford University]].<ref>http://dailynous.com/2016/04/27/wolff/</ref>\u000a\u000aHe was formerly the secretary of the [[British Philosophical Association]] and has been Editor and then honorary secretary of the [[Aristotelian Society]], which publishes ''Proceedings of the Aristotelian Society''. Recently, Wolff's work has specialized in [[disadvantage]] and [[Egalitarianism|equality]] and [[public policy]] decision making.\u000a\u000aAs a scholar on the topic of [[Marxism]], Wolff published "Marx and Exploitation", an article about Marxist thinking, in ''The Journal of Ethics''. He also co-edited (with Michael Rosen) ''Political Thought'' (ISBN 0-19-289278-9), an introductionary reader on political philosophy.\u000a\u000aHe has also published a critique of [[Robert Nozick]]'s ''[[Anarchy, State, and Utopia]]'' called ''Robert Nozick: Property, Justice and the Minimal State'', a short book on [[Karl Marx]], ''Why Read Marx Today?'', and ''An Introduction to Political Philosophy''. He currently writes a monthly column for ''[[The Guardian]]'' and occasionally blogs at [[Brian Leiter]]'s "[[Leiter Reports]]" blog.\u000a\u000aJonathan Wolff presented a 4-part series about the UK's National Health Service for the BBC's Radio 3 programme 'The Essay' during the week of 27 July 2009.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00cc959 |title=BBC Radio 3 - The Essay, Doctoring Philosophy |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2009-07-31 |accessdate=2013-08-01}}</ref> The series, entitled "Doctoring Philosophy", marked the 60th anniversary of the NHS and commenced by studying the philosophical background which led to the foundation of the service and the changing definitions of sickness and health. It went on to explore entitlement, issues of equality of service, and issues of priorities in a world of universal access.\u000a\u000aHe is currently a member of the [[Nuffield Council on Bioethics]]. He has been a member of two of the Council\u2019s Working Parties; on ''the ethics of animal research'',<ref>[http://www.nuffieldbioethics.org/animal-research/ Nuffield Council on Bioethics official website-animal research]</ref> and ''the ethics of personalised healthcare''<ref>[http://www.nuffieldbioethics.org/personalised-healthcare-0/ Nuffield Council on Bioethics official website-personalised healthcare]</ref>\u000a\u000a== Bibliography ==\u000a;Books\u000a*{{cite book | title = Robert Nozick: Property, Justice and the Minimal State | publisher = Polity in association with Basil Blackwell | location = Oxford | year = 1991 | isbn = 978-0-7456-0603-3 }}\u000a*{{cite book | title = An Introduction to Political Philosophy, Third Edition | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford Oxfordshire | year = 2015 | isbn = 9780199658015 }}\u000a*{{cite book |author=Michael Rosen | title = Political Thought | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford Oxfordshire | year = 1999 | isbn = 0-19-289278-9 }}\u000a*{{cite book | title = Why Read Marx Today? | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford Oxfordshire | year = 2002 | isbn = 978-0-19-280335-1 }}\u000a*{{cite book | title = Disadvantage, co authored with Avner de Shalit | publisher = Oxford University Press, USA | location = New York | year = 2007 | isbn = 978-0-19-927826-8 }}\u000a*{{cite book | title = Ethics and Public Policy: A Philosophical Inquiry | publisher = Routledge | location = Abingdon | year = 2011 | isbn = 9780415668538 }}\u000a*{{cite book | title = The Human Right to Health | publisher = W. W. Norton & Company, USA | location = New York | year = 2012 | isbn = 978-0-393-07900-5 }}\u000a\u000a;Journal articles\u000a* {{Cite journal | last = Wolff | first = Jonathan | title = Scanlon on well-being | journal = [[Ratio (journal)|Ratio]] | volume = 16 | issue = 4 | pages = 332\u2013345 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1046/j.1467-9329.2003.00227.x | date = December 2003 | url = http://dx.doi.org/10.1046/j.1467-9329.2003.00227.x | ref = harv | postscript = .}}\u000a::''See also'': {{Cite journal | last = Scanlon | first = T.M. | author-link = T. M. Scanlon | title = Replies | journal = [[Ratio (journal)|Ratio]] | volume = 16 | issue = 4 | pages = 424\u2013439 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1046/j.1467-9329.2003.00231.x | date = December 2003 | url = http://dx.doi.org/10.1046/j.1467-9329.2003.00231.x | ref = harv | postscript = .}}\u000a\u000a== References ==\u000a{{Reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a{{wikiquote}}\u000a* [http://www.homepages.ucl.ac.uk/~uctyjow/ Wolff's website at UCL]\u000a* [http://www.philosophypathways.com/newsletter/issue53.html "Four Forms of Redistribution" by Jonathan Wolff]\u000a* [http://www.philosophypathways.com/newsletter/issue53.html "A Comment on Professor Wolff's 'Four Forms of Redistribution'" by Tony Flood']\u000a\u000a{{Subject bar\u000a| portal1=Philosophy\u000a| portal2=Biography\u000a| portal3=United Kingdom\u000a}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Wolff, Jonathan}}\u000a[[Category:1959 births]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:Academics of University College London]]\u000a[[Category:English political philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Marxist theorists]]\u000a[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:British ethicists]]\u000a[[Category:English male writers]]
